First, we define the functions that we are going to use in the notebook.

Secondly, we take out the different franchises we want to use.

To continue, we select the franchises we are interested in, in this case Dunkin, Starbucks, Burger King, Taco Bell and Mcdonalds.

Continuing with the introduction of the work done in this notebook, we made two dynamic graphs to continue with the visualisation of these and to provide more information about the market study we are carrying out.

Finally, we have decided to carry out a sentimental analysis that will be completed later with a neural network as a model of automatic learning, in this section we have subdivided it as follows:

  • Global analysis of all the franchises as an example.

def plot_wordcloud(df, column, title):
    df['text_clear'] = df[column].apply(preprocess)
    wc = WordCloud(width=1600, height=800, random_state=1, max_words=200000000)
    wc.generate(str(df['text_clear']))
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,5), facecolor='k')
    plt.title(title, fontsize=15,color='white')
    plt.imshow(wc, interpolation='bilinear')
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.tight_layout(pad=10)
    return plt.show()

 
# Defining some functions for later use for wordcloud
def preprocess(x):
    x = re.sub('[^a-z\s]', '', x.lower())                  # get rid of noise
    x = [w for w in x.split() if w not in set(stopwords)]  # remove stopwords
    return ' '.join(x) # then join the text again



def get_compound_score(text):
  scores = sia.polarity_scores(text)
  return scores['compound']

# For generating word pairs
import collections
from nltk.corpus import stopwords

# these are helper functions 

def tokenize(s):
    """Convert string to lowercase and split into words (ignoring
    punctuation), returning list of words.
    """
    word_list = re.findall(r'\w+', s.lower())
    filtered_words = [word for word in word_list if word not in stopwords.words('english')]
    return filtered_words


def count_ngrams(lines, min_length=2, max_length=4):
    """Iterate through given lines iterator (file object or list of
    lines) and return n-gram frequencies. The return value is a dict
    mapping the length of the n-gram to a collections.Counter
    object of n-gram tuple and number of times that n-gram occurred.
    Returned dict includes n-grams of length min_length to max_length.
    """
    lengths = range(min_length, max_length + 1)
    ngrams = {length: collections.Counter() for length in lengths}
    queue = collections.deque(maxlen=max_length)

    # Helper function to add n-grams at start of current queue to dict
    def add_queue():
        current = tuple(queue)
        for length in lengths:
            if len(current) >= length:
                ngrams[length][current[:length]] += 1

    # Loop through all lines and words and add n-grams to dict
    for line in lines:
        for word in tokenize(line):
            queue.append(word)
            if len(queue) >= max_length:
                add_queue()

    # Make sure we get the n-grams at the tail end of the queue
    while len(queue) > min_length:
        queue.popleft()
        add_queue()

    return ngrams

def print_most_frequent(ngrams, num=10):
    """Print num most common n-grams of each length in n-grams dict."""
    for n in sorted(ngrams):
        print('----- {} most common {}-word phrase -----'.format(num, n))
        for gram, count in ngrams[n].most_common(num):
            print('{0}: {1}'.format(' '.join(gram), count))
        print('')
